<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12016f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12016f">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12016f"> 16(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ Vauban devant Coutances</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Roc, ville, ch&acirc;teau-fort, formant une masse homog&egrave;ne, d&apos;une seule pouss&eacute;e hardie. En pr&eacute;sence de ce magnifique morceau d&apos;architecture et d&apos;histoire, nous revient le mot de Vauban en face du d&ocirc;me de Coutances: &ldquo;Qui donc a jet&eacute; ces pierres dans le ciel?&rdquo; <font color="green">[Rock, city, castle-fort, one homogeneous mass, of one bold thrust. In the presence of such a magnificent piece of architecture and history, we think of what Vauban said in front of the dome at Coutances: &ldquo;Who has thrown these stones into the heavens?&rdquo;]</font> <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLL"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1892) 129</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Fr. <i>Devant</i>: in front og. The Cathedral of Coutances, like Mont Saint-Michel, is an impressive example of vertical Gothic architecture in Normandy. Marshal Vauban (seventeeth-century military engineer and geographer) wrote that its tower must have been built by &lsquo;a sublime madman&rsquo;. He was also impressed by Mont Saint-Michel. </mm> </dd></dl>
